-- Enrichment marathon batch: Decidim, Deel, DeepSeek, DefectDojo, DelightChat, Deluge, Demio, Dependency-Track

-- ── Decidim ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Decidim is a free, open-source platform for participatory democracy that lets governments and organizations run proposals, budgets, and voting online.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Community-run open-source project (not a company)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Barcelona, Spain (Decidim Association)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Catalan$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Finnish$q$, $q$Polish$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Decidim: Open-Source Participatory Democracy Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Decidim is a free, open-source platform for citizen participation, proposals, budgeting, and elections. Used by governments and institutions worldwide.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Decidim (Catalan for 'we decide') is a free and open-source digital platform for participatory democracy that enables governments, public institutions, universities, and civil-society organizations to run online and hybrid citizen-participation processes such as proposal collection, participatory budgeting, public deliberation, surveys, assemblies, and secure elections. The project originated with Decidim.Barcelona, launched by Barcelona City Council on 31 January 2016 as part of the council's 2016-2019 citizen-participation action plan. The very first version was built as a fork of Consul, the open-source platform created by Madrid City Council (decide.madrid.es), reflecting the inter-municipal collaboration between the Ahora Madrid and Barcelona en Comu governments that emerged from Spain's 2015 municipal elections and the broader 15-M ('Indignados') movement's push for open, publicly owned democratic infrastructure. In 2017 the Decidim codebase was rewritten from scratch as a modular Ruby on Rails framework and began to be adopted by other cities and institutions beyond Barcelona. In 2019, Barcelona City Council transferred control of the Decidim trademark and codebase to the newly formed Decidim Association, a nonprofit that now stewards the project on behalf of a global community. Development and governance happen in the open on Metadecidim, a meta-participation space where developers, designers, public officials, researchers, and citizens co-design the platform's roadmap; the source code is published on GitHub under the AGPL-3.0 license, guaranteeing that any hosted derivative of Decidim must also make its source available.

Architecturally, Decidim is not a single hosted product but a self-hostable framework: any organization can deploy its own instance on its own infrastructure (Docker images and Rails deployment guides are provided) or engage one of the many third-party agencies and public-sector IT providers in the Decidim ecosystem to host, customize, and support an installation. There is no vendor lock-in and no mandatory license fee, since the software itself is entirely free; costs, when they exist, come from hosting, integration, and support services rather than the platform itself. Organizations configure 'participatory spaces' -- processes, assemblies, consultations, conferences, and initiatives -- and enrich each space with reusable components: Proposals (crowdsourced idea submission, amendment, and voting), Budgets (participatory budgeting where citizens allocate real public funds across competing projects), Meetings (in-person and online event scheduling with minutes and attendance), Surveys, Debates, Blogs, Pages, Accountability (tracking follow-through on commitments), and Elections (a secure, auditable digital voting booth supporting census upload or token-based voter verification). This component-based architecture lets a city run a multi-year strategic plan with public meetings and proposal collection in one space, while running a fast, single-issue participatory budget vote in another, all on the same underlying platform and user accounts.

Decidim's most prominent deployments include Barcelona itself, which has run several cycles of city-wide participatory budgeting through the platform, as well as instances used by the European Commission, the government of Mexico City, Helsinki, and dozens of other municipalities and regional governments across Europe and Latin America, along with universities and NGOs. Because it is free, source-available under a strong copyleft license, and backed by an active nonprofit and community rather than a single commercial vendor, Decidim is frequently chosen by public administrations that are required or prefer to use open, auditable civic-tech infrastructure rather than proprietary SaaS. Its closest competitors are Consul (the Madrid-originated open-source platform it originally forked from), CitizenLab/Go Vocal, Bang the Table/EngagementHQ, Balancing Act, and OpenGov's community engagement tools; Decidim differentiates itself primarily through its open governance model, AGPL licensing, breadth of built-in democratic mechanisms, and its academic/civic-tech lineage tied to Barcelona's technological-sovereignty movement.

Because Decidim is free software with no official pricing tiers, the cost of adoption is really the cost of hosting and configuration: small deployments can run on a modest VPS, while large national or EU-wide consultations require more substantial infrastructure and DevOps support, typically procured through the Decidim Association's directory of certified service providers. The platform's interface has been localized into dozens of languages via community translation on Crowdin, including English, Spanish, Catalan, French, German, Italian, Portuguese, Finnish, and Polish, making it viable for multilingual, multi-jurisdiction deployments. Target users are municipal and regional governments, national ministries, supranational bodies like the EU, universities, and any civil-society organization that needs an auditable, standards-based way to run public consultations, participatory budgets, or elections without depending on a single commercial vendor's roadmap or terms of service. Because the codebase is open and self-hosted, Decidim also appeals to public bodies with strict data-sovereignty or procurement requirements that rule out closed SaaS competitors.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7a37a860-0053-444d-834e-ac1979dd8720';

