-- ── Deel ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Deel is a global payroll, HR, and Employer of Record platform that helps companies hire, pay, and manage employees and contractors in 150+ countries.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Per-employee/contractor subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$29/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$4,000-9,600+ employees (estimates vary by source)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA (fully distributed/remote team)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Deel: Global Payroll, EOR & HR Platform | 150+ Countries$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Deel is a global hiring platform offering EOR, contractor management, payroll, and HR tools in 150+ countries. Backed by $979M+ in funding, valued at $17.3B.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Deel is a global people-management platform that combines Employer of Record (EOR) services, contractor payments, global payroll, HR information systems (HRIS), immigration support, and equity management into a single system so that companies can legally hire, pay, and manage employees and independent contractors in more than 150 countries without setting up their own local legal entities. The company was founded in 2019 by Alex Bouaziz (CEO) together with co-founder Shuo Wang, initially focused on solving cross-border contractor payments before rapidly expanding into full Employer of Record services, which let a client company employ a worker in a country where the client has no legal entity by having Deel's local entity serve as the legal employer of record while the client directs the day-to-day work. Deel is headquartered in San Francisco but operates as a fully distributed, remote-first company, a structure the founders have described as both a philosophical choice and a practical necessity for a company selling global employment infrastructure.

Deel has raised roughly $979 million across eight funding rounds from investors including Ribbit Capital, Andreessen Horowitz (a16z), Coatue Management, Y Combinator, and Spark Capital, among others. Its most recent disclosed raise was a $300 million Series E co-led by Ribbit Capital, a16z, and Coatue, which valued the company at $17.3 billion, making Deel one of the most highly valued private HR-tech companies globally. As of 2026 the company reports roughly $1.4 billion in annual recurring revenue (up from around $1 billion the prior year), processes about $22 billion in payroll annually, and serves more than 35,000 customers and 1.5 million-plus workers across 150-plus countries. In February 2026, Deel filed a confidential S-1 with regulators, signaling active preparation for a public listing, though as of this writing it remains a private company. Headcount estimates vary significantly by data source and time period, ranging from roughly 4,000 to over 9,600 employees, reflecting Deel's rapid and sometimes volatile hiring trajectory.

Functionally, Deel's platform is organized around several core products that can be purchased independently or combined. Deel EOR lets a client hire a full-time employee in a country without a local entity; Deel's local subsidiary becomes the legal employer, issuing compliant employment contracts, running local payroll and tax withholding, administering statutory benefits, and handling onboarding/offboarding, typically priced around $599 per employee per month for standard countries and roughly $899 per employee per month for higher-complexity 'enterprise' EOR countries. Deel Contractor Management, aimed at companies paying independent contractors rather than employees, starts at roughly $49 per contractor per month and covers compliant contract generation, multi-currency payouts in 120-plus currencies, and tax form generation (such as 1099s or W-8BENs). For situations where contractor misclassification risk is a concern, Deel offers Contractor of Record (COR) at a higher price point (around $325/month) that converts the arrangement into a compliant, Deel-managed relationship. Deel Global Payroll, for companies that already have their own legal entities in a country and just need payroll processing, is priced from around $29 per employee per month. A US-specific Professional Employer Organization (PEO) offering is also available for domestic US employees, priced around $125 per employee per month. Across all of these products, customers get access to a unified HRIS dashboard covering time-off tracking, expense management, org charts, and reporting, plus 24/7 in-app support. One notable operational detail buyers frequently flag is that Deel typically requires a one-month gross-salary deposit per EOR employee, refunded roughly 30 days after offboarding, and applies a currency-conversion markup (commonly cited around 0.6% to 2% above the mid-market rate) when funding and payroll currencies differ.

Deel's target customers span the full range from early-stage startups making their first international hire to large enterprises running distributed teams of hundreds or thousands of workers; its scale-based volume discounts mean effective per-employee EOR pricing for large enterprise commitments (50-plus employees, multi-year terms) can be reported as low as roughly $315 to $400 per employee per month. Deel differentiates itself from competitors primarily on breadth (payroll, EOR, contractor management, immigration, and equity in one platform), country coverage (150-plus), and speed of onboarding, and has increasingly layered AI-assisted compliance and HR features on top of the core product. Its most direct competitors in the global-employment-platform category include Remote, Rippling, Papaya Global, Multiplier, Oyster HR, and Globalization Partners (G-P), with Rippling in particular being a frequent point of public rivalry given overlapping HRIS ambitions. Deel is available as a web application with companion iOS and Android mobile apps for employees and admins to manage time off, expenses, and payslips, and exposes APIs for HRIS and payroll integrations with tools like NetSuite, QuickBooks, and various applicant tracking platforms.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8ba3ae79-2d46-4049-881a-4cf6417f0f42';

