-- ── DeepSeek ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DeepSeek is a Chinese AI lab that builds open-weight large language models like DeepSeek-V3 and R1, offered via a free chat app and a low-cost API.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (free chat app; pay-per-token API)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Hangzhou, Zhejiang, China$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Chinese (Mandarin)$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DeepSeek: Open-Weight AI Models & Chat App | V3, R1$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DeepSeek is a Chinese AI lab offering free chat apps and low-cost API access to open-weight models DeepSeek-V3 and R1, rivaling top Western LLMs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DeepSeek is a Chinese artificial intelligence company that designs, trains, and releases large language models, most notably the general-purpose DeepSeek-V3 family and the reasoning-focused DeepSeek-R1 model, both of which are released as open-weight models that developers can download, run locally, and fine-tune. The company was founded in Hangzhou, Zhejiang, in July 2023 by Liang Wenfeng, a Chinese entrepreneur who is also co-founder of the quantitative hedge fund High-Flyer, which owns and funds DeepSeek. As of public disclosures, Liang personally holds a large majority stake in DeepSeek (reported at roughly 84% via two holding entities), and the company has largely self-funded its research using capital and compute resources built up through High-Flyer's algorithmic trading business rather than raising traditional venture capital, a structure that distinguishes it from most Western frontier AI labs such as OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google DeepMind.

DeepSeek rose to global prominence in January 2025 when it released DeepSeek-R1, a reasoning model using chain-of-thought techniques that benchmarked competitively against OpenAI's o1 model on math, coding, and logic tasks, while being released with open weights and at a fraction of the training and inference cost publicly attributed to comparable Western models. This triggered widespread commentary about the efficiency of DeepSeek's training methods (including techniques like mixture-of-experts architectures and reinforcement-learning-based post-training) and briefly moved global technology markets as investors reassessed assumptions about the capital intensity of frontier AI development. DeepSeek has continued to iterate on its model lineup, including DeepSeek-V3 (a general-purpose model with a large context window, roughly 164K tokens, strong at coding, reasoning, and multilingual tasks) and subsequent versions such as DeepSeek-V4, with the lab positioning itself around a strategy of matching or approaching frontier-model quality at substantially lower training and serving cost.

Access to DeepSeek's models comes in two main forms. The DeepSeek chat product is a free consumer-facing AI assistant, available via web browser at chat.deepseek.com as well as official native apps for iOS and Android, that lets anyone converse with the models, use a Deep Think reasoning mode, upload files, search the web, and sync chat history across devices; the official app is free, though DeepSeek has also warned that many unofficial 'DeepSeek' branded apps in mobile app stores are unaffiliated wrappers that may charge for functionality the real app provides at no cost. Developers and businesses can instead call DeepSeek's models programmatically through its API, priced per million tokens on a pay-as-you-go basis; as of 2026, DeepSeek-V3 is priced at roughly $0.269 per million input tokens and $0.40 per million output tokens, while DeepSeek-R1 (whose chain-of-thought reasoning generates substantially more output tokens per response) is priced at roughly $0.80 per million tokens for both input and output. DeepSeek-V4 pricing has been reported around $0.30 per million input tokens and $0.50 per million output tokens. The API also offers a context-caching discount, billing cache hits at roughly 10% of the standard input rate, which materially lowers cost for applications with repeated or templated prompts.

DeepSeek's models support well over 50 languages, with particularly strong performance in English and Mandarin Chinese and solid coverage of major European and Asian languages, making the platform attractive for multilingual applications. The company's primary differentiator versus competitors like OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and Meta is the combination of open-weight licensing (which lets enterprises self-host models for data-sovereignty or cost reasons), aggressive low pricing on hosted API access, and research transparency around training methodology, all delivered from a lab that, unlike most large AI labs, is not backed by major outside venture or hyperscaler investment but rather by a proprietary trading firm's balance sheet. This has made DeepSeek's models popular building blocks for third-party inference providers, open-source tooling, and cost-sensitive enterprise deployments, while also drawing scrutiny in some Western markets over data handling, since DeepSeek's hosted consumer services route data through infrastructure based in China, leading several governments and enterprises to restrict or ban official DeepSeek apps on official devices even as the open-weight models themselves remain widely used when self-hosted elsewhere. Target users span individual developers experimenting with a free, capable assistant; startups and enterprises building cost-sensitive AI features on the API or self-hosted weights; and researchers studying efficient large-model training techniques. Competitors include OpenAI (ChatGPT/GPT models), Anthropic (Claude), Google (Gemini), Meta (Llama, also open-weight), Mistral, xAI's Grok, and other Chinese labs such as Alibaba's Qwen and Moonshot AI's Kimi.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2db08197-cb69-436a-acb8-e03d763b0ab6';

