-- ── DefectDojo ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DefectDojo is an open-source DevSecOps and ASPM platform that aggregates, deduplicates, and manages vulnerabilities from 200+ security scanning tools.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source with paid Pro tier$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DefectDojo: Open-Source Vulnerability Management & ASPM$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DefectDojo is an OWASP flagship open-source platform for vulnerability management, DevSecOps automation, and ASPM, with a Pro tier from $300/month.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DefectDojo is an open-source vulnerability management and Application Security Posture Management (ASPM) platform used by security and DevSecOps teams to aggregate, correlate, deduplicate, triage, and report on findings from a wide range of security testing tools. The project traces its origins to 2013 and was released as open-source software in 2015; it is written in Python using the Django web framework and has been developed in close partnership with the OWASP Foundation, under which it holds status as an OWASP Flagship Project -- a designation reserved for mature, widely adopted projects that demonstrate strategic value to application security. The community/open-source edition of DefectDojo is distributed under the permissive BSD 3-Clause license, and the project reports substantial real-world adoption, with figures cited around 45 million-plus downloads, roughly 4,800 GitHub stars, close to 490 contributors, and more than 10,000 organizations using the platform.

At its core, DefectDojo is designed to solve a problem common to any organization running multiple security scanners: each tool (SAST, DAST, SCA, container scanning, infrastructure scanning, penetration testing reports, and more) produces its own report format and its own view of 'a vulnerability,' and without a central system the same underlying flaw gets reported, tracked, and remediated multiple times across different tools and teams. DefectDojo solves this by ingesting structured results from 200-plus supported security tools (including popular options like OWASP ZAP, Burp Suite, Checkmarx, Semgrep, Trivy, and Nessus, plus many CI/CD-native scanners), normalizing them into a common data model organized around products, engagements, tests, and findings, then applying deduplication logic so that the same vulnerability discovered by multiple tools (or the same tool run repeatedly) is merged into a single trackable finding rather than duplicated. From there, teams can triage findings, assign severity and risk ratings, track remediation status and SLAs, generate compliance-oriented reports, and expose metrics on security posture trends over time, functionally turning a pile of raw scanner output into an organized, auditable vulnerability management workflow that integrates into CI/CD pipelines via its REST API.

Alongside the free, self-hosted Community Edition, DefectDojo also offers a commercial Pro edition, sold both as a cloud-hosted SaaS product and as an on-premises installation, currently offered as a subscription starting at roughly $300 per month (with promotional discounts around 30% observed at various points). DefectDojo Pro adds capabilities not present in the community edition: enhanced dashboards and executive-level reporting, expanded risk-scoring and prioritization logic, a tunable deduplication engine that lets administrators fine-tune how findings are merged, a customizable rules engine for automating triage decisions, out-of-the-box connector integrations with enterprise-grade scanners such as Checkmarx One and Burp Suite Enterprise, and -- reflecting the broader industry shift toward AI-assisted security operations -- a feature called DefectDojo Sensei, an AI module aimed at helping teams interpret and act on findings faster, as well as Model Context Protocol (MCP) support that lets large language model assistants query and act on DefectDojo data directly. DefectDojo offers prospective Pro customers a two-week trial to evaluate the paid tier before committing.

DefectDojo's primary users are application security engineers, DevSecOps teams, and security leadership at organizations of any size that run more than one scanning tool and need a single source of truth for vulnerability status, a category that spans startups adopting their first SAST/DAST pipeline up to large enterprises consolidating security tooling across hundreds of development teams. Because the community edition is free, fully self-hostable, and integrates broadly, DefectDojo is frequently adopted by security teams that want to avoid vendor lock-in or per-seat SaaS pricing common among commercial ASPM vendors. Its competitors span both the open-source and commercial ends of the market: open-source alternatives and adjacent projects include OWASP Dependency-Track (software-composition/SBOM-focused rather than general vulnerability aggregation), while commercial ASPM and vulnerability-management competitors include products like Faraday, Vulcan Cyber, Kenna Security (Cisco), Brinqa, and larger platform players such as Snyk and Wiz that bundle scanning and vulnerability management together. DefectDojo differentiates itself primarily on tool-agnostic breadth (200-plus integrations), a mature and long-running open-source core that avoids lock-in, and a clear free-to-paid upgrade path (Community to Pro) for teams that later need enterprise scanner connectors, AI-assisted triage, or vendor support. DefectDojo deployments are typically run via Docker Compose, Kubernetes/Helm charts, or a hosted Pro instance, and the platform exposes a full REST API and CLI tooling so that findings ingestion and reporting can be automated as a stage inside CI/CD pipelines (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins, and others), making it as much a piece of security-automation infrastructure as a standalone dashboard.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '717823fe-8010-4821-a2b2-2263a7afbe21';

