-- ── DelightChat ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DelightChat is an omnichannel helpdesk and WhatsApp marketing platform that helps D2C and e-commerce brands manage WhatsApp, Instagram, and email support.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription with free trial$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$29/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~15 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Delaware, USA (legal); distributed team across India and Southeast Asia$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DelightChat: WhatsApp Helpdesk & Marketing for E-commerce$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DelightChat unifies WhatsApp, Instagram, and email support with WhatsApp marketing automation for D2C brands. Plans start at $29/month with a 14-day trial.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DelightChat is a customer support and WhatsApp marketing platform built specifically for direct-to-consumer (D2C) and e-commerce small and medium-sized businesses, unifying high-volume conversational channels -- the official WhatsApp Business API, Instagram Direct Messages, Facebook Messenger -- with traditional support channels like email and website live chat into a single shared team inbox. The company was founded in 2020 by Preetam Nath and Sankalp Jonna, who built the product around a specific pain point they observed among e-commerce brands: as WhatsApp and Instagram became primary customer-contact channels alongside traditional email, support teams were forced to juggle multiple disconnected apps and lost visibility into a shopper's full conversation history across channels. DelightChat's team is small, reported at roughly 13 to 16 employees, distributed primarily across India and Southeast Asia, with the company's registered legal headquarters in Delaware, United States.

The product is delivered both as a standalone web application and as a native Shopify app (listed on the Shopify App Store as 'DelightChat: WhatsApp Marketing + Helpdesk'), reflecting its tight focus on the Shopify-centric D2C ecosystem, though it also serves merchants on other e-commerce stacks. Functionally, DelightChat splits into two connected halves. The Helpdesk half centralizes customer conversations from WhatsApp, Instagram, Facebook, email, and live chat into one inbox with shared team visibility, assignment rules, canned responses, and order-context lookups (pulling a customer's Shopify order history directly into the conversation view so agents don't have to switch tabs to answer 'where is my order' questions). The Marketing half uses the official WhatsApp Business API to send bulk broadcast campaigns, abandoned-cart recovery messages, order and shipping notification flows, and other automated WhatsApp sequences, positioning WhatsApp as both a support and a revenue-recovery channel rather than purely a customer-service tool. An AI chatbot capability is also part of the newer product surface, aimed at automating first-response handling across Instagram, Facebook, email, and WhatsApp before escalating to a human agent.

DelightChat's pricing is structured in tiers: publicly listed plans include a Startup tier around $29 per month, a Scale tier around $99 per month, and a Growth tier around $299 per month, with feature and usage limits (number of WhatsApp conversations, team seats, automation rules) scaling up at each tier; the company also offers a 14-day free trial, after which several sources report an effective starting price closer to $49 per month depending on the specific plan and promotional terms active at signup. As a young, independent, VC-light company relative to category leaders, DelightChat has reported modest but real revenue traction, with third-party estimates citing roughly $1.8 million in annual recurring revenue and a company valuation in the single-digit millions, positioning it as a lean, profitable-leaning niche player rather than a venture-scale unicorn.

DelightChat's target customer is squarely the growing D2C or e-commerce SME that has outgrown generic helpdesk tools like Zendesk or Freshdesk for WhatsApp-specific workflows, or has outgrown using the WhatsApp Business App manually and needs the official WhatsApp Business API with multi-agent support and marketing automation. Its most direct competitors include Wati, Interakt, Gallabox, MyAlice, and Zoko -- all WhatsApp Business API-focused helpdesk/marketing tools serving a similar SME e-commerce audience, especially strong in markets like India and Southeast Asia where WhatsApp commerce is particularly dominant -- as well as broader omnichannel helpdesk platforms like Gorgias and Richpanel that serve e-commerce brands but with less WhatsApp-specific depth. DelightChat differentiates itself through its combination of helpdesk and WhatsApp marketing automation in one product, tight Shopify integration showing order data inline with conversations, and pricing aimed at SMEs rather than enterprise budgets. The product is delivered entirely as a web application (with a companion Shopify app listing) rather than native desktop or mobile apps, and support is available through email, live chat, WhatsApp, and a self-serve help center. Because DelightChat is API-based, using Meta's official WhatsApp Business Platform rather than an unofficial or scraped WhatsApp integration, messaging is compliant with WhatsApp's commerce policies and templated-message approval process, which is a meaningful trust signal for merchants wary of account bans that can occur with unofficial WhatsApp automation tools.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c3f9f0e9-8131-4e11-ac4b-7ce69fe029a0';

