-- ── Deluge ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Deluge is a free, open-source, cross-platform BitTorrent client with a client/daemon architecture supporting web, console, and desktop interfaces.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2006, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Russian$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Deluge: Free Open-Source BitTorrent Client$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Deluge is a free, open-source, cross-platform BitTorrent client with a lightweight daemon, web UI, and plugin system. Available for Windows, Mac, and Linux.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Deluge is a free and open-source, cross-platform BitTorrent client written primarily in Python, released under the GPL-3.0-or-later license. The project's first version was released on September 25, 2006; it was originally going to be named something else but was renamed 'Deluge' because a project called gtorrent already existed on SourceForge, and because the developers had by then extended their ambitions beyond a GNOME-only client to something that could run on any platform supporting GTK. Deluge is a community/volunteer open-source project rather than a commercial company, hosted and developed collaboratively on GitHub under the deluge-torrent organization, with no venture funding, corporate ownership, or paid tiers -- the entire application, including all official plugins, is free to download, use, and modify.

Architecturally, Deluge is built around libtorrent, a widely used C++ networking library that implements the actual BitTorrent protocol logic (peer discovery, piece selection, encryption, and transfer), which Deluge wraps via its own Python bindings. Starting with version 1.0, Deluge adopted a client/daemon split: the core torrent-handling engine (deluged) runs as a background daemon/service, independent of any particular user interface, which can then be controlled remotely by one or more separate front-ends -- a native GTK desktop GUI, a text-based console interface (useful for headless servers and SSH sessions), and a browser-based Web UI that lets users manage torrents remotely from any device with a browser. This separation is one of Deluge's most distinctive architectural traits relative to many other BitTorrent clients, since it allows a user to run the daemon persistently on a home server, NAS, or seedbox and then connect to it from a desktop GUI, phone browser, or terminal without the interface needing to run on the same machine as the actual downloading process. Deluge has supported magnet links since version 1.1.0 (released January 2009) and, per the 0.5.x rewrite, added protocol encryption, peer exchange (PEX), and UPnP support; it also implements DHT (Distributed Hash Table) for trackerless torrent discovery, Local Peer Discovery, NAT-PMP for automatic port forwarding, and Web Seeds (HTTP-based torrent seeding).

A large portion of Deluge's advanced functionality is delivered through an official plugin system rather than being bundled into the core application, keeping the base client lightweight while still letting power users add capabilities such as RSS-based auto-downloading, bandwidth scheduling, notifications, label-based torrent organization, and various third-party-contributed extensions. Deluge runs natively on Linux (its primary and most actively maintained platform, commonly available through distribution package repositories), and has official or community-supported builds for Windows and macOS (historically distributed via MacPorts, with more recent native builds also available), making it genuinely cross-platform despite its GTK/GNOME origins. Because the daemon-and-remote-UI architecture is particularly well suited to always-on, headless environments, Deluge is a popular choice for users running dedicated download boxes, NAS devices (including via community packages for Synology and QNAP systems), and remote seedboxes, where the Web UI or console interface lets them manage transfers without needing a full desktop environment.

As free, open-source software, Deluge's target users are individuals and technically inclined users who want a lightweight, scriptable, remotely manageable torrent client without subscription costs or bundled adware -- a category of user who values control and self-hosting over the more polished, sometimes ad-supported or freemium experience offered by some competing clients. Its most direct competitors in the open-source BitTorrent client space are qBittorrent (widely seen today as Deluge's closest and most actively developed rival, with a similarly ad-free, open-source Qt-based interface and its own built-in search and RSS features), Transmission (particularly popular on macOS and Linux for its minimalism), and, among closed-source/freemium options, uTorrent and BitTorrent (both owned by Rainberry, Inc.), which bundle advertising and, historically, extra features gated behind a paid 'Pro' tier that Deluge and its open-source peers do not have. Deluge's translated interface is maintained by a volunteer community on Launchpad and covers dozens of languages beyond English, including German, French, Spanish, Italian, Russian, Chinese, and Japanese, among others, reflecting its long-running global open-source contributor base. Deluge is fully free with no pricing tiers, no ads, and no telemetry-driven monetization, consistent with its GPL-3.0-or-later licensing, which requires that any distributed modified version of the software also remain open source.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a4888a56-3678-4b59-b919-440fd6bf1847';

