-- ── Dependency-Track ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Dependency-Track is a free, open-source OWASP platform that uses SBOMs to continuously identify and manage risk across the software supply chain.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free/Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Dependency-Track: Open-Source SBOM & Supply Chain Security$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Dependency-Track is a free OWASP platform for SBOM analysis, tracking components, vulnerabilities, and policy across your software supply chain at scale.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Dependency-Track is a free and open-source platform for software supply chain security, built around the concept of the Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) rather than traditional point-in-time dependency scans. The project began in 2013 under the OWASP Foundation umbrella (created by Steve Springett, who remains its lead architect) and has since become one of OWASP's Flagship Projects, a status reserved for projects that demonstrate strategic value and sustained maturity within the application security community. Dependency-Track is released under the Apache 2.0 license, making it freely usable, modifiable, and embeddable -- including in commercial products -- without royalty obligations, and the project reports adoption by more than 20,000 organizations worldwide.

The platform's central architectural idea is to treat the SBOM as the unit of truth for a software project's composition. Rather than scanning source code or a build artifact fresh each time a report is needed, Dependency-Track ingests CycloneDX-format SBOMs (an OWASP-originated, now internationally standardized SBOM format) generated by build tooling, CI/CD pipelines, or dedicated SBOM-generation tools, and continuously tracks every component -- libraries, containers, operating system packages, firmware, and services -- across every version of every project in an organization's portfolio. Because the SBOM captures a project's full dependency tree at a point in time, Dependency-Track can retroactively surface risk the moment a new vulnerability is disclosed for any component already recorded in a previously ingested SBOM, without needing to re-scan the original codebase; this 'ingest once, monitor continuously' model is what most clearly distinguishes SBOM-based platforms like Dependency-Track from traditional Software Composition Analysis (SCA) tools that primarily scan on demand. Dependency-Track continuously cross-references components against multiple vulnerability intelligence sources, verifies upstream component integrity, and prioritizes remediation using signals like EPSS (Exploit Prediction Scoring System) scores to help teams focus on vulnerabilities that are both severe and realistically exploitable rather than triaging every CVE with equal urgency. The platform also produces and consumes CycloneDX VEX (Vulnerability Exploitability eXchange) and VDR (Vulnerability Disclosure Report) documents, letting organizations formally communicate whether a given vulnerability in a component is actually exploitable in their specific product context -- an increasingly important capability for organizations subject to supply-chain security regulation and customer due-diligence questionnaires.

Dependency-Track underwent a significant architectural overhaul with its version 5.x release line, which rebuilt the core engine for higher availability and much larger scale. The redesigned engine supports stateless application instances that coordinate purely through PostgreSQL (without requiring a separate message broker), enabling active/active high-availability deployments across multiple zones. Early adopters running v5 alpha and beta builds reportedly ingested upwards of 20,000 SBOMs per hour, and some organizations have been reported running single v5 instances holding more than 250,000 SBOMs representing tens of millions of individual software components -- throughput and portfolio scale that puts Dependency-Track firmly in enterprise-grade territory despite it being entirely free, open-source software. As with most OWASP projects, Dependency-Track has no official commercial SaaS offering or paid tier from the OWASP Foundation itself; organizations self-host it (commonly via Docker containers, with deployment guides for Kubernetes and cloud environments) and, where commercial support or managed hosting is desired, turn to third-party vendors and consultancies in the OWASP ecosystem rather than a single official vendor.

Dependency-Track's primary users are application security and DevSecOps teams, particularly at organizations with large, multi-project software portfolios who need centralized, continuous visibility into open-source and third-party component risk -- a need sharpened in recent years by supply-chain-security regulation and frameworks (such as US federal software supply chain requirements around SBOMs for government software vendors) that increasingly make SBOM production and monitoring a compliance requirement rather than a best practice. It integrates naturally into CI/CD pipelines via its REST API, accepting SBOMs generated by tools like CycloneDX's own generators, Syft, or various language-specific SBOM plugins, and is frequently deployed alongside complementary OWASP tooling such as DefectDojo (which focuses on broader vulnerability management and finding deduplication across many types of security tools, including SBOM-based results) and OWASP Dependency-Check (a traditional, on-demand SCA scanner that Dependency-Track can also ingest results from). Its competitors in the broader software composition analysis and SBOM space include commercial platforms such as Snyk, Sonatype (Nexus Lifecycle/IQ), JFrog Xray, Mend (formerly WhiteSource), and Anchore, most of which bundle SBOM/SCA capability into broader paid application-security suites -- Dependency-Track differentiates itself by being purpose-built around SBOM ingestion specifically, free and open source with no per-seat or per-scan pricing, and backed by OWASP's nonprofit, vendor-neutral governance rather than a single commercial vendor's roadmap.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b102eee5-b364-47b7-9569-b256d99e7549';

